				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I'd like to see open-source with crowd-funded commissions of fixes/improvements, if it's not being done. Free fails I believe for two reasons.<br /><br />Free doesn't give reliable information to the author about what's most important to users, because they don't have to give anything up to make requests. If they were paying money, they would only pay for things that were valuable to them, and would think of what was most important. And then the aggregate of users would show which was most valuable. This valuation would also give the author an idea of whether it was worth even implementing, based on how much was offered.<br /><br />Free doesn't support the author's own costs in implementing things. The author has to bring in money to pay for living and the tools to make the software. If there is no payment, then the author will only work on things that are more enjoyable than the other things he could be doing with his free time. With payment, he can reduce his other work and work on the open-source software more, and justify less-enjoyable activities. The level of payment that users offer allows the all-important economic calculation to occur, figuring what balance between all these things is most effective.<br /><br />The paid commission approach is nice because it doesn't &quot;taint&quot; the program; the program is a kind of communally-owned resource that it just happens that mainly one person is adding to, which people chip in to pay for.<br /><br />...<br /><br />My personal experience with open-source programs is that many are fantastically buggy (gnome-mplayer, I'm looking at you, you buggy POS that core dumps half the time when I close it). It's pathetic. Almost every one looks like someone had a lot of enthusiasm to make a program, but ran out part way through and just skipped finishing the rest of the features. Perhaps that's why command-line programs are generally better, because they mostly focus on doing one thing well.<br /><br />...<br /><br />Re: koitsu's comments on bailing on one's own work, that is the single biggest thing that hurts to this day about all my emulation work. In hindsight (always 20/20!) I see how much better I could have done things to make them more maintainable to others. It's funny you mention kids, because it feels like I just abandoned these kids in a state that nobody else could continue. (save the &quot;oh you did some great stuff&quot; because I know I did, as this is something that ties in with other issues I have and will take a long time to resolve)<br /><br />In retrospect I totally dig the almost impersonal way of doing things as is done on Wikis, where the tone of everything is similar and extremely dry. The work stands above any one author and everyone can add to it without upsetting its consistency.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

