						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">koitsu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">3) Publicly explain why (and always be honest) they can't (or don't want to) maintain the software any longer</div><br /><br />You mention this once or twice, though I can't think of any reason someone would need to give. &quot;I don't want to&quot; should be good enough. You don't need to have an explanation for not doing free work. What's a valid explanation in your mind? What's an invalid one? If the reasons are personal, then that person has a right to keep them private. If they're legal, that should be explained if it would affect future users of the project. If the reason is just disinterest, I don't see why that's not valid in itself.<br /><br />I would agree that there are good practices to take when abandoning something that people use. You should at least plant a flag to declare this, so that anyone coming to it will know what the current state of maintenance is. A handoff is better, if such a person is available, but there probably isn't in most cases. Even if it's just abandoned without a word, leaving an open source project is still a step above abandoning a free but closed source project, at least.<br /><br />I might think less of someone for abandoning a project in a poor way, but I wouldn't hold anything against someone for failing to give a reason for stopping their volunteer software development.</div>

