				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">rainwarrior wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">koitsu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">3) Publicly explain why (and always be honest) they can't (or don't want to) maintain the software any longer</div><br />You mention this once or twice, though I can't think of any reason someone would need to give. &quot;I don't want to&quot; should be good enough. You don't need to have an explanation for not doing free work. What's a valid explanation in your mind? What's an invalid one? If the reasons are personal, then that person has a right to keep them private. If they're legal, that should be explained if it would affect future users of the project. If the reason is just disinterest, I don't see why that's not valid in itself.</div><br />It's perfectly valid -- &quot;I'm no longer interested&quot; is a public explanation of why, as is &quot;personal reasons&quot;, or pretty much anything else.<br /><br />My recommendation stems from boatloads of projects (again, see Sourceforge, Freshmeat, and even github (despite how young it is)) where the maintainer(s) have disappeared.  Support requests go unheeded, Emails (if you can dig them up) go unanswered, that sort of thing; nobody knows if the project is abandoned or not, and if so no one knows why.  It's even worse when the source repo is controlled/owned by 1 person and so nobody can really improve on the existing repo's code (I've seen this happen a lot with github).  Anyway, the needs vary per project; I'll give you 3 examples: the proftpd project, the Tomato project, and a project which will remain nameless.<br /><br />With proftpd, the (sole) maintainer just disappeared -- after many months, Emails started bouncing, mailing lists continued to function albeit suffering from spam and security holes, and the author was no where to be found.  Nobody knew if he had died or what.  It took years to &quot;regain control&quot; over this whole situation -- and as I understand it, the situation actually happened two different times (my memory could be wrong here, I'm having to think back to 1996 or thereabouts).  I remember this situation because I used proftpd at the time (when Parodius was running Linux) and the massive numbers of security holes kept piling up with no response from the author, and no way to truly rectify the issue &quot;officially&quot; other than Jimmy Bob Jhonka releasing patches, while Derpa Herpa Xavier Sr. releases different patches, yadda yadda.  After 5 or 6 security issues + that nonsense, I gave up on the daemon entirely.<br /><br />With Tomato, the situation is similar -- nobody is sure if the author exists/is alive because he doesn't respond to Email.  I'm not talking about support requests, I'm talking about forked projects who need clarification on the license (if you can even call it that) used throughout the source code.  It's believed that he's alive/around but chooses to intentionally not respond (this is based on, for example, that his domain is registered until 2022, but the last domain update/modification was in December 2012).  Regardless, as a result, nobody dares touch/change certain pieces of the code (as well as certain pieces of the HTML/CSS/Javascript) because nobody can get clarification on the license.<br /><br />The nameless project situation was this -- there was a fellow who maintained a very good set of bare metal software (applied KISS principle, did not add unnecessary features, hated creeping featurism, etc.) and was very communicative with end-users.  Over time, the guy started acting strangely and eventually disappeared.  After much prodding, it was admitted privately to 1 or maybe 2 people at most that his wife had died and as a result he had effectively just &quot;shut down&quot;.  None of this was public (and still isn't).  So users of this code (as well as people who helped participate with in that project) didn't know what to do for support, and public disclosure of what had happened could never occur due to the private nature of the situation.  Users were left in the dark with no (public) reason.<br /><br />Now you see why a public statement of some kind is useful when leaving a project, vs. just going AWOL.  The reason / what's said doesn't matter as much as the fact that <strong>something</strong> is said -- that's the responsibility aspect I speak of.</div>

