					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I see your point koitsu, the problem is that *anyone*, even young and healthy, can suddently die in an accident. People who know this person &quot;in real life&quot; probably had few ideas of the free software the guy wrote and was actively maintening.<br /><br />I agree about that less than 2% of people are able to debug software and so on. Myself I typically use print statements as a debug method, or any other method that involves visible output, rather than an actual debugger. Only in some particular situation I bothered to use an actual debugger.<br /><br />Reardless, uderstanding someone else's code is often more time consuming and more complex than writing yourself a clone of the code, implementing the same functionality. It's completely counter intuitive, but I figured out this is sadly true (at least for me). Of course it depends of the coding style, language, etc, etc... but overal that's the sad reality.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">There is good and bad software of both kinds. A great deal of free software is buggy, unfinished, abandoned, poorly written, unmaintainable, etc. If Bregalad hasn't found this to be the case I think he is either lucky, or willfully ignoring it.</div><br />No, I'm not willfulyl ignoring anything. Of course I had some things not work so well under Linux, but overall I have to say the free softs I use are just as in average better than some of the proprietary softs I have to use.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">A big reason not to support shareware, commercial, or any other kind of closed-source software is that some day all the source code will disappear with the company, even if it had value to the community.</div><br />In fact same could be said with free software. Anything that is created is doomed to die some day. I don't see how it could be otherwise, sadly.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Parents in some industrialized countries do tend to expect that from school systems. &quot;It takes a village&quot; and all that.</div><br />Then they are horrible parents. I mean having children and refusing to educate them is a very outragous thing, that sandly increases dramastically those years.</div>

